  "prompt": "Why do people with white skin get burnt easily?",
  "response": "People with white skin often have less melanin, which is the pigment that gives skin its color and provides some protection against the sun's ultraviolet (UV) rays. Melanin helps to absorb and scatter UV radiation, reducing the amount of damage it can cause to the skin. \n\nWhen skin is exposed to UV radiation without sufficient melanin protection, it can lead to sunburn. This is an inflammatory response to damage caused by UV rays, which can harm the DNA in skin cells, leading to redness, pain, and peeling. People with fairer skin, especially those with very light or red hair and blue or green eyes, have less melanin and are therefore more susceptible to sunburn.\n\nTo protect against sunburn, it's important for everyone, but especially those with lighter skin, to use sunscreen, wear protective clothing, and limit sun exposure during peak UV hours.",
